<section xml:id="sec-Equations-of-Lines"
    xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Equations of Lines</title>
    <p>
        Let's write parametric equations of the line through the points <m>A = (4,-7,8)</m> and <m>B = (2,-8,-3)</m>. The point <m>A</m> is the base-point.
    </p>
    <p>
        First we define the points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> as vectors.
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            var('t')
            A = vector([4, -7, 8])
            B = vector([2, -8, -3])
        </input>
        <output>
            
        </output>
    </sage>
    <p>
        Compute the direction vector.
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            d = B - A
            d
        </input>
        <output>
            
        </output>
    </sage>
    <p>
        Write the parametric equations of the line through the points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> by accessing the components of the point vector <em>A</em> and the direction vector <em>d</em>.  
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            # Parametric equations
            x = A[0] + d[0] * t
            y = A[1] + d[1] * t
            z = A[2] + d[2] * t
            (x, y, z)
        </input>
        <output>
            
        </output>
    </sage>
</section>
